spans.text: these various scenes of gilded life , Of fraud , ambition , policy , and strife ;
, where false notions erring I pursue , And with the plausible confound the true : Correct with all the freedom that I write ; And guide my darkened reason with thy light
my darkened reason with thy light
tell how wretched this our mortal state

Fate A thousand evils which ourselves create
the current of too weak a tide
But wilful man inverting her decrees , When young would govern , and when old would please
the fruits his autumn should bestow
with loathing to her venal charms
it's Providence's fault , If thus untimely all her gifts are sought , If summer-crops which must decay we keep , And in the winter would the harvest reap
it's Providence's fault , If thus untimely all her gifts are sought , If summer-crops which must decay we keep , And in the winter would the harvest reap
More than we can , lose what we might obtain
that joined the sated pair once fled
their haunts , their pasture , and their bed
no after-weight of forms or laws
we in the wood , the sea , or plain , One ever elected over the rest to reign
they their equal , sometime less , revere
Who weeps with mutual pain her useless charms
of our wishes cursed , Bathed in untasted springs we die with thirst
the liquid sweet of every flower
From my loved friend these precious hours I waste , Why do I vainly here thy absence
